# orcasecurity_integration_webhook_template (Resource)

Manages a Webhook integration in Orca Security.

Under the hood this creates an entry under `POST /api/external_service/config`
with `service_name = "webhook"`. Orca posts alert events to the configured
`webhook_url`. The companion data source `orcasecurity_webhook` can read
existing webhooks for use as inputs to automations.

## Supported integration types

This single resource manages **every webhook-delivered integration** in Orca.
Several integrations that appear as distinct tiles in the Orca UI are stored by
the platform as webhook variants — they share one `service_name = "webhook"`
config and differ only by the `type` discriminator. Pick the target with the
`type` argument:

| `type`      | Orca UI integration | Notes |
|-------------|---------------------|-------|
| `common`    | Generic Webhook     | Any customer-controlled HTTP endpoint. |
| `torq`      | Torq                | Torq trigger webhook URL. |
| `tines`     | Tines               | Tines inbound webhook URL. |
| `opus`      | Opus                | Opus webhook URL. |
| `coralogix` | Coralogix           | Coralogix ingest URL. |
| `panther`   | Panther             | Panther HTTP source URL. |

All variants take the same arguments (`webhook_url`, `api_key`, `body_fields`,
`custom_headers`) — there is no separate resource per vendor. To integrate with
Torq, Tines, Opus, Coralogix, or Panther, use this resource with the matching
`type`.

## Example Usage

### Basic example

{{tffile "examples/resources/orcasecurity_integration_webhook_template/resource.tf"}}

### Sourcing the API key from HashiCorp Vault

```terraform
data "vault_generic_secret" "wh" {
  path = "secret/webhook/orca"
}

resource "orcasecurity_integration_webhook_template" "from_vault" {
  template_name = "alerts-webhook"

  config = {
    webhook_url = "https://example.com/hooks/orca"
    type        = "common"
    api_key     = data.vault_generic_secret.wh.data["api_key"]
  }
}
```

### Vendor variant (Torq, Tines, Opus, Coralogix, Panther)

Vendor integrations use the same resource — just set `type` to the vendor and
point `webhook_url` at the vendor endpoint:

```terraform
resource "orcasecurity_integration_webhook_template" "torq" {
  template_name = "torq-alerts"

  config = {
    webhook_url = "https://hooks.torq.io/v1/webhooks/xxxxxxxx"
    type        = "torq"
    api_key     = var.torq_api_key
  }
}
```

## Argument Reference

* `template_name` — (Required, String) Identifier for the integration as shown
  in the Orca UI and used as the lookup key for update/delete operations.
  Changing this forces a new resource.
* `is_enabled` — (Optional, Bool) Whether the integration is enabled. Defaults
  to `true`.
* `is_default` — (Optional, Bool) Whether this integration is the
  organisation's default webhook configuration. Defaults to `false`.
* `business_units` — (Optional, List of String) Optional list of Orca business
  unit IDs that may use this integration. Leave unset to make the integration
  available to all business units the caller can access.
* `config` — (Required, Block) Webhook configuration:
    * `webhook_url` — (Required, String) Destination URL Orca posts events to.
    * `type` — (Required, String) Which webhook-delivered integration to
      manage. One of `common`, `torq`, `tines`, `opus`, `coralogix`,
      `panther` — see [Supported integration types](#supported-integration-types).
    * `api_key` — (Optional, String, Sensitive) Optional API key sent with
      each webhook request. Not populated on import — see
      [Import](#import).
    * `body_fields` — (Optional, List of String) Optional list of Orca alert
      fields to include in the webhook request body. Leave unset to send the
      default payload.
    * `custom_headers` — (Optional, Map of List of Object) Optional custom
      HTTP headers keyed by header name. Each value is a list of
      `{ custom = "<value>" }` objects so a single header name can carry
      multiple values.

## Attribute Reference

* `id` — (String) Orca external service config identifier (UUID).

## Notes

* The webhook `api_key` lives inside the JSON config (not in SSM), so Orca's
  GET response includes it. The provider still treats it as the source of
  truth from your configuration: it is marked `sensitive = true` to keep it
  out of CLI output, and refresh/Read never overwrites the value you supplied
  with the API echo (so a re-encoded or stripped echo can't cause drift). The
  trade-off is that import cannot recover it — see [Import](#import).
* Use an encrypted remote backend (S3 + KMS, GCS, Terraform Cloud, etc.) and
  restrict read access to the state — `api_key` and any sensitive header
  values land in state regardless of the `sensitive = true` flag.

## Import

Webhook integrations can be imported by their `template_name`:

```bash
terraform import orcasecurity_integration_webhook_template.example webhook_name
```

**Set `api_key` after import.** Import does not populate `config.api_key` —
the provider treats it as a user-supplied secret and never overwrites it from
the API on refresh, so the imported state leaves it empty. After importing,
add `api_key` to your configuration (matching the value already stored in
Orca) so the first `terraform apply` does not clear it. If the integration has
no API key, leave `api_key` unset.

